{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:20:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13148"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13148"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.28,0.03,0.53,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5585"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96317"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5585"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13148"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78987"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4847"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14857"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30912"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32977"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33299"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96317"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of abdominal pain, constipation, and fatigue. She has a history of Stage II HER2-positive breast cancer diagnosed three months ago, currently being treated with trastuzumab and doxorubicin. She takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears lethargic but oriented. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Physical examination is otherwise unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 137 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChloride 105 mmol/L (95-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 4.1 mmol/L (3.5-5.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium 3.35 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPhosphate 0.65 mmol/L (0.8-1.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase 85 U/L (30-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea 6.4 mmol/L (2.3-7.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine 91 \u00b5mol/L (40-90)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR \u0026gt;90 mL/min/1.73 m2 (\u226590)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EParathyroid hormone (PTH) 0.3 pmol/L (1.6-6.9)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely mechanism of hypercalcaemia?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primary hyperparathyroidism","Osteolytic bone metastases","Vitamin D toxicity","Tumour secretion of PTHrP","Granulomatous disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptomatic hypercalcaemia, characterised by fatigue, constipation, and confusion. The initial workup of hypercalcaemia involves determining whether it is PTH-dependent or PTH-independent. A suppressed PTH level, as seen here, indicates PTH-independent hypercalcaemia and narrows the differential diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour secretion of PTHrP\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis. PTHrP-mediated hypercalcaemia is the most common mechanism of malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia, particularly in breast cancer. The combination of high calcium, low phosphate, and suppressed PTH is characteristic. PTHrP mimics PTH\u0027s effects on bone resorption and renal calcium reabsorption while suppressing endogenous PTH production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hyperparathyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by elevated or inappropriately normal PTH levels with hypercalcaemia. The suppressed PTH in this case excludes this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteolytic bone metastases\u003C/strong\u003E can cause hypercalcaemia through local bone destruction. While this is a common mechanism in breast cancer, this patient was diagnosed with non-metastatic (Stage II) disease. Additionally, osteolytic metastases typically present with normal or elevated phosphate levels and elevated alkaline phosphatase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E causes increased calcium absorption from the gut and typically presents with elevated phosphate levels, unlike this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous disease\u003C/strong\u003E causes hypercalcaemia through dysregulated production of 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D, leading to increased intestinal calcium absorption. This typically presents with elevated phosphate levels and is more commonly seen in conditions like sarcoidosis or tuberculosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment involves urgent management of hypercalcaemia with intravenous fluids and bisphosphonates, alongside treatment of the underlying malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hypercalcaemia with suppressed PTH suggests PTH-independent causes such as malignancy, vitamin D toxicity, or granulomatous disease.","PTHrP-mediated hypercalcaemia is the most common mechanism of malignancy-associated hypercalcaemia.","The combination of high calcium, low phosphate, normal alkaline phosphatase, and suppressed PTH is characteristic of PTHrP-mediated hypercalcaemia."],"references":["Adeyinka A, Bashir K. Tumor Lysis Syndrome. (2022) StatPearls [Internet]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK518985/","Body JJ. Bone metastases and tumor-induced hypercalcemia. (1992) Current Opinion Oncology. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/1511019/","Acharya, Roshan et al. \u201cAn unusual case of severe hypercalcemia: as dehydrated as a bone.\u201d (2021) Journal of community hospital internal medicine perspectives. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7850409/","Vakiti A, Anastasopoulou C, Mewawalla P. Malignancy-Related Hypercalcemia. (2023). StatPearls [Internet]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482423/","Stewart AF. Clinical practice. Hypercalcemia associated with cancer. N Engl J Med. 2005 Jan 27;352(4):373-9. doi: 10.1056/NEJMcp042806. PMID: 15673803."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78987"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13148"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78987"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-31T21:03:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T08:56:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5585"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96317"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{